Invoking: `validate` with `{'patch': '--- a/ext/dom/document.c\n+++ b/ext/dom/document.c\n@@ -1996,7 +1996,12 @@\n \t\t\tintern->document = NULL;\n-\t\t\tif (php_libxml_increment_doc_ref((php_libxml_node_object *)intern, newdoc) == -1) {\n-\t\t\t\tRETURN_FALSE;\n-\t\t\t}\n+\t\t\tif (php_libxml_increment_doc_ref((php_libxml_node_object *)intern, newdoc) == -1) {\n+\t\t\t\tif (intern->document) {\n+\t\t\t\t\tphp_libxml_decrement_doc_ref((php_libxml_node_object *)intern);\n+\t\t\t\t\tintern->document = NULL;\n+\t\t\t\t}\n+\t\t\t\tRETURN_FALSE;\n+\t\t\t}\n \t\t\tintern->document->doc_props = doc_prop;\n'}`
responded: The memory leak described in the sanitizer output is due to a missing deallocation of the memory allocated with `emalloc` in the function `php_libxml_increment_doc_ref` (`object->document = emalloc(sizeof(php_libxml_ref_obj));`). This occurs specifically when `php_libxml_increment_doc_ref` allocates a new document reference object, but the corresponding destructor/decrement call is not made if the function (such as `dom_load_html`) returns early (`RETURN_FALSE;`) and skips over the normal release path.

**In the control flow of dom_load_html:**  
- If `php_libxml_increment_doc_ref((php_libxml_node_object *)intern, newdoc)` returns -1 (allocation failed), `RETURN_FALSE;` is executed right away.
- However, the newly created `object->document` must be cleaned up/freed before returning, otherwise it is leaked.

**Patch:**
Add a proper deallocation (call to `php_libxml_decrement_doc_ref`) before `RETURN_FALSE;` in the error path (line 1997 in ext/dom/document.c) in `dom_load_html`.

Here is the patch:

```diff
--- a/ext/dom/document.c
+++ b/ext/dom/document.c
@@ -1996,7 +1996,10 @@
 			intern->document = NULL;
-			if (php_libxml_increment_doc_ref((php_libxml_node_object *)intern, newdoc) == -1) {
-				RETURN_FALSE;
-			}
+			if (php_libxml_increment_doc_ref((php_libxml_node_object *)intern, newdoc) == -1) {
+				if (intern->document) {
+					php_libxml_decrement_doc_ref((php_libxml_node_object *)intern);
+					intern->document = NULL;
+				}
+				RETURN_FALSE;
+			}
 			intern->document->doc_props = doc_prop;
```

This ensures any newly allocated `document` is properly freed in the error path, and that the leak is fixed. I will now validate this patch.

